98:  * yet achieves the same behavior.)
99:  *
100:  * <p>The use of a metaclass also allows us to compute a mapping from Attributes to small integers
101:  * and share this between all rules of the same metaclass. This means we can save the attribute
102:  * dictionary for each rule instance using an array, which is much more compact than a hashtable.
103:  *
104:  * <p>Rule classes whose names start with "$" are considered "abstract"; since they are not valid
105:  * identifiers, they cannot be named in the build language. However, they are useful for grouping
106:  * related attributes which are inherited.
107:  *
108:  * <p>The exact values in this class are important. In particular:
109:  *
110:  * <ul>
111:  *   <li>Changing an attribute from MANDATORY to OPTIONAL creates the potential for null-pointer
112:  *       exceptions in code that expects a value.
113:  *   <li>Attributes whose names are preceded by a "$" or a ":" are "hidden", and cannot be redefined
114:  *       in a BUILD file. They are a useful way of adding a special dependency. By convention,
115:  *       attributes starting with "$" are implicit dependencies, and those starting with a ":" are
116:  *       late-bound implicit dependencies, i.e. dependencies that can only be resolved when the
117:  *       configuration is known.
118:  *   <li>Attributes should not be introduced into the hierarchy higher then necessary.
119:  *   <li>The 'deps' and 'data' attributes are treated specially by the code that builds the runfiles
120:  *       tree. All targets appearing in these attributes appears beneath the ".runfiles" tree; in
121:  *       addition, "deps" may have rule-specific semantics.
122:  * </ul>
123:  *
124:  * TODO(bazel-team): Consider breaking up this class in more manageable subclasses.
125:  */
